body:
To reproduce:

```verilog
module t ();

   wire true;
   not1 a(true, '0);

   wire false;
   not1 b(false, '1);

   initial begin
      if (true != '1) $stop;
      if (false != '0) $stop;
      $finish;
   end

endmodule // t

primitive not1 (q, d);
   output q;
   input  d;
   table
      0 : 1;
      1 : 0;
      x : x;
   endtable
endprimitive // not1
```

And the test driver code:

```python3
import vltest_bootstrap
test.scenarios('vlt_all')
test.compile()
test.execute()
test.passes()
```

The expected result is that the `true` and `false` wires will be 1 and 0, respectively. However, they are both set to X (depending on the value of the `--x-assign` command-line argument).

